author: Gary Howes
news_feed.body:
- RBA to make key call on asset purchases

- Could open the door to a stronger AUD

- But Covid cases could prompt caution

- Dovish surprise could see GBP/AUD test 1.85

Image © Crawford Forum, Reproduced Under CC Licensing

GBP/AUD reference rates at publication:

Spot: 1.8395

Bank transfer rates (indicative guide): 1.7740-1.7868

Money transfer specialist rates (indicative): 1.8220-1.8254

The Pound-to-Australian Dollar exchange rate (GBP/AUD) has fallen into the middle of its June-July range at 1.8390, an entirely predictable move given the gravitas of the looming policy update from the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA).

The RBA's July policy update will see Governor Philip Lowe and his team decide the future of the RBA's asset purchase programme and given the heightened market focus on the decision analysts say volatility in the Australian Dollar is possible.

"These policies help lower lending rates in the economy. They also help to produce a weaker Australian dollar than otherwise would be the case," says Besa Deda, Chief Economist at St. George Bank in Sydney.

Therefore, a strong signal that the RBA is planning to exit its unconventional monetary policy stance will be interpreted by investors as being supportive of the Australian Dollar and could put GBP/AUD under some pressure.

Above: The GBP/AUD has settled into the middle of its recent range ahead of the July RBA call.

The RBA decision however comes with the country's most populous state remaining in lockdown and with other states maintaining a high vigilance to further outbreaks of Covid-19.

The economic cost of the latest series of Covid measures - that saw areas of Queensland, the Northern Territory and Western Australia lock down - will not be lost on the RBA.

Economists at St. George Bank estimate that the two-week lockdown in New South Wales alone will cost the economy around A$750 million a week, and possibly as much as A$1 billion a week, provided the lockdown is relatively short.

A longer lockdown will have a bigger impact say economists.

Should the Covid situation prompt an air of caution amongst RBA policy makers then the Australian Dollar could lose ground against its peers.

"Consumers and businesses are grappling with the uncertainty of how long it will take for this outbreak to be contained in New South Wales and for restrictions to ease," says Deda.

The weekly Roy Morgan consumer confidence survey showed confidence fell 4.6% in Sydney in the week ended June 27, which captured only some of the lockdown.

But beyond the short-term the Australian economy remains buoyant and some economists warn that ultra-low interest rates and quantitative easing (the buying of government bonds to support the economy) are not consistent with an economy with such a bright outlook.

Employment is a key indicator of economic health observed by the RBA: In February the unemployment rate was 6.4% and the RBA's Statement on Monetary Policy (SOMP) forecast that it would be 6.5% by the time of the July update ahead of 5.5% in June 2022 and 5.25% by June 2023.

The unemployment rate is already back down at 5.1%.

The RBA therefore faces something of a balancing act on responding to strong labour market statistics and uncertainty over the domestic path of the pandemic, which could ultimately open the door to some currency-moving surprises.

"We expect that the RBA will likely want to avoid being seen as an early adopter of tapering in order to avoid any upside pressure on the exchange rate. If the Bank does decide on a more flexible approach to asset purchases, Lowe is likely to trend carefully to communication the central bank’s dovish credentials," says Jane Foley, Senior FX Strategist at Rabobank.

The asset purchase programme sees it control the cost of finance in the economy, ensuring it remains low enough to keep businesses investing and consumers spending, thereby protecting against any economic slowdown.

One method of keeping borrowing costs low sees the RBA buys bonds to keep the yield paid on the government's three-year bond at 0.10% in a programme called Yield Curve Control (YCC).

Keeping the yield on this bond low is important given much of Australia's lending system is structured around it.

The bond currently being targeted is the three-year bond that expires in April 2024.

The first major decision for the RBA will be whether or not to keep targeting the April 2024 bond or move on and target the November 2024 bond.

St. George Bank anticipate the RBA will keep its target pegged to the April 2024 bond.

"If the peg were extended to the November 2024 bond, it would imply the RBA does not intend to increase the cash rate until 2025, which is too late given the robust economic conditions," says Deda.

The market tends to agree with this call with Marshall Gittler at BD Swiss Group saying the impact of such a decision could be positive for Australian Dollar valuations, although he suspects the decision is in the market already.

A decision to target the November 2024 bond would therefore come as something of a surprise to the market and could well trigger Aussie Dollar weakness, which could in turn allow GBP/AUD to rally back towards its 2021 high just above 1.85.

The quantitative easing programme (the second element of the asset purchase programme which was only introduced in November 2020) meanwhile sees the RBA buy A$5BN worth of government bonds per week with maturities of 5 to 10 years over a period of about six months.

The value of purchases will total A$100 billion and it is due to expire in September.

"The RBA needs to decide whether to extend this programme and if there is an extension, what form this extension might take," says Deda.

St. George Bank anticipate the quantitative easing programme will be extended but they join the market consensus in anticipating the RBA will adopt a more flexible approach to the weekly purchase amount.

"The RBA is likely to review this program again around December. We still expect the RBA to continue the program to the middle of 2022, but the pace of purchases in 2022 is likely to be lower than in 2021," says Deda.

The RBA decision is due at 05:30 BST.

news_feed.headline: GBP/AUD Exchange Rate Dips as UK Covid-19 Cases Continue to Grow
news_feed.body:
The Pound Australian Dollar exchange rate dipped this morning despite Prime Minister Boris Johnson expected to give the thumbs up for the lifting of lockdown restrictions on July 19 later today. With approximately 25,000 people proving positive for the virus for each day in the UK, however, GBP investors are remaining notably cautious.

What’s Been Happening: ‘Aussie’ Weakens in Risk-Off Trade

The Pound strengthened against the ‘Aussie’ last week as weakening risk sentiment weakened demand for the risk-sensitive Australian Dollar.

Rising Covid-19 infections rose in key economies – including Europe and China – stoked concerns over the global economic recovery.

In Australian economic data, last week saw the publication of the latest AiG manufacturing PMI for June, which confirmed forecasts and rose from May’s 61.8 to 63.2, buoying confidence in the nation’s manufacturing sector.

Last week saw the new UK Health Secretary, Sajid Javid, maintain his positive view to lifting lockdown restrictions later this month. But with rising Covid-19 cases throughout England, Pound investors remained largely cautious.

The latest UK manufacturing PMI for June was also downwardly revised to 63.4. But the outlook for the nation’s economy remained positive thanks to encouraging comments from Downing Street about the final easing of lockdown restrictions on July 19.

Three Things to Watch Out for This Week

RBA Interest Rate Decision

The Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) is expected to hold its cash rate at the record low of 0.1. But could dovish commentary from the bank’s Governor, Philipe Lowe, limit investor demand for the Australian Dollar?

UK Covid-19 News

If – as is widely expected – the UK Government continues to maintain that it is on track to lifting lockdown restrictions later in July, then we could see the GBP/AUD exchange rate head higher this week.

UK GDP

This week will see the release of the UK’s latest GDP figures, with a positive release in May potentially propelling Sterling higher.

Pound Australian Dollar Forecast

The GBP/AUD exchange rate could head higher this week as the UK edges closer to easing lockdown restrictions on July 19. We could see growing confidence in the nation’s economy translate to a stronger Sterling.

news_feed.headline: British Pound: GBP Advances Vs. EUR, USD, AUD, NZD And CAD As End To England's Lockdown To Be Confirmed
news_feed.body:
Confident Sterling start to the week, Pound Advance Against all Majors

The Pound Sterling has posted gains on Monday with expectations of net capital inflows into the UK.

GBP/EUR

Prime Minister Johnson will make a statement later on Monday and is expected to announce that plans for an easing of coronavirus restrictions in England will go ahead in England on July 19th which helped support Pound sentiment.

There were mixed comments on inflation and monetary policy from ECB officials over the weekend with Schnabel stating that an overshoot in inflation is necessary and proportionate to escape from low inflation, but fellow member Knot was more concerned over inflation and that the asset-purchase programme should be wound down from March.

Bank President Lagarde is expected to maintain a dovish stance which will sap Euro support.

The Euro has remained vulnerable on the crosses with the Pound to Euro (GBP/EUR) exchange rate securing net gains to 1.1665.

GBP/USD

The US dollar corrected weaker following Friday’s jobs data with a stronger than expected headline increase in non-farm payrolls offset by a small increase in the unemployment rate.

Expectations of an early Federal Reserve reduction in bond purchases were scaled back slightly which curbed underlying dollar support, although underlying confidence in the currency held firm.

Overall, risk appetite held firm on Monday following strong Wall Street gains on Friday, although Asian markets were unable to make headway. The takeover offer for Morrison’s supermarket helped underpin expectations of capital inflows.

The US Independence Day holiday will dampen trading volumes and the Pound to Dollar (GBP/USD) exchange rate posted a further limited recovery from 10-week lows below 1.3750 and traded at 1.3840 at the European open.

GBP/AUD

Domestic data was mixed with further gains in job ads for June, but a larger than expected decline in building approvals for the month.

There were some concerns over the Chinese data as the Caixin PMI services index slowed sharply to a 14-month low of 50.3 from 55.1 previously which could have some impact in dampening Australian exports if manufacturing also slows.

There was inevitable caution ahead of Tuesday’s Reserve Bank of Australia policy decision with the bank set to review the asset-purchase programme.

The Pound to Australian dollar (GBP/AUD) exchange rate secured net gains to 1.8400 from 1.8365 lows.

GBP/CAD

Canadian markets will be open on Monday, but the US closure will have an impact in curbing trading activity. The latest Bank of Canada business outlook survey will be released later on Monday and will be important for underlying growth expectations and central bank policy.

Oil prices remained an important focus with OPEC scheduled to hold a third day of talks in an attempt to reach agreement on production quotas with the UAE resisting an output deal last week.

Crude prices held firm which helped underpin Canadian dollar sentiment.

After opening around 1.7020 in Asia on Monday, the Pound to Canadian dollar (GBP/CAD) exchange rate strengthened to 1.7075.

GBP/NZD

The ANZ commodity-price index increased 0.8% for June after a 1.3% gain the previous month with a 27.8% increase over the year from 25.2% previously. ANZ also reported further upward pressure on shipping costs and prices which will maintain speculation that the Reserve Bank of New Zealand will move towards higher interest rates.

Confidence in the outlook for New Zealand commodity prices continued to provide underlying support for the New Zealand dollar with underlying strength in terms of trade important for longer-term currency trends.

The Pound to New Zealand dollar (GBP/NZD) exchange rate opened around 1.9650 in Asia on Monday before net gains to 1.9700 at the European open.

news_feed.headline: Are GBP/AUD longs looking attractive as Australia head into further lockdowns?
news_feed.body:
UK savings on the rise

The UK savings rate has risen to 19.1% in Q1 versus 16.1% in Q2 according to the UK’s Office for National Statistics. The UK’s savings rate measures the income that households have saved vs a proportion of their disposable income. This latest print is second only to the jump to 25.9% in April and June last year when the first round of COVID-19 lockdowns landed. This latest print is the second-highest savings rate on record.

High savings rate is a promising sign for an early UK boost, but tail risks remain.

The UK’s fast vaccination rate and the seemingly broken link between cases and hospitalizations mean that the GBP should see a boost between now and the end of the year. Yes, the BoE has focused on the downside risks. Perhaps there is a hint of caution here because the impact of Brexit has at least partially been concealed by the COVID-19 crisis and the UK balance of payments is still in deficit. This deficit means that the UK imports more goods, services, and capital than it exports. So, it is borrowing from other countries to pay for its imports. If this continues over the longer term it means that the UK will need to go into debt to pay for that consumption.

GBP vs AUD

One nice potential trade setting up is that as the UK looks like coming OUT of restrictions on July 19 Australia is heading back INTO restrictions. A low vaccination rate in Australia, combined with the rapidly spreading delta variant means that Australia has a battle on its hands to try and hold back the virus. The RBA meet next week and that is going to hunker down for another financial fight. Therefore, on the balance of probabilities, GBPAUD makes sense.

news_feed.headline: Pound Australian Dollar Exchange Rate Forecast: GBP/AUD To Firm?
news_feed.body:
GBP/AUD Climbs on Australian Surge in Coronavirus Cases

The Pound to Australian Dollar (GBP/AUD) exchange rate strengthened over the last week, with the Aussie having been beset by a surge in cases of the Delta coronavirus variant.

Sterling’s upside was limited by concerns over the future of the UK economy, including staff shortages, post-furlough unemployment and overinflation fears.

Pound (GBP) Exchange Rates' Gains Capped by Inflation and Post-Furlough Fears

The Pound started the week on the back foot, despite renewed optimism over the reopening of the UK economy.

On Monday evening, the new health secretary Sajid Javid updated MPs on the government’s outlook for the final stage of easing lockdown restrictions. Javid said the government saw ‘no reason’ not to remove the remaining restrictions on 19 July.

Despite this positive news, many voiced concerns over the spread of the Delta variant, which weighed on the Pound.

As the week progressed, fears around the future of UK jobs offset some positive economic news.

The latest UK consumer credit report showed that, for the first time since August 2020, consumers were borrowing more than they saved, pointing to an increase in consumer confidence and a recovering economy.

However, with the government’s furlough scheme winding down from 1 July, many organisations, including the Institute for Fiscal Studies, warned of a steep drop in income and increased unemployment as businesses respond by making redundancies.

The risk of staff shortages added to the employment worries, with the Confederation of British Industry calling on government to relax its post-Brexit immigration policies to avoid a skill shortage in the labour market.

Further pressuring the Pound was a dovish response from the Bank of England (BoE) following overinflation concerns raised by the BoE’s departing Chief Economist, Andy Haldane.

Haldane warned that the UK faces a ‘dangerous moment’ with regards to rising inflation, forecasting 4% inflation by the end of this year.

In response, BoE Governor Andrew Bailey hit back, saying:

‘We expect this rise in inflation to be a temporary feature of the bounce-back. The reasons for taking this view are well-founded, it is not a vain hope or a matter of whistling in the wind.’

This reaffirmation of the central bank’s dovish approach to policy dented Sterling.

Despite all this, the Pound Australian Dollar exchange rate strengthened on AUD’s weakness. The UK’s strong economic recovery and reopening optimism fortified GBP enough for the currency to climb against AUD as the latter slid.

Australian Dollar (AUD) Exchange Rates Tumble as Delta Variant Spreads

The Australian Dollar has been dragged down amid an ongoing coronavirus outbreak in Australia.

The Delta variant of the virus managed to break through Australia’s defences over the last fortnight, after the country managed to avoid any major outbreaks since the pandemic began.

On Friday 25 June, Sydney went into lockdown. As the week progressed, six more cities came under restriction measures, affecting almost half the country’s population.

A major concern is Australia’s low vaccination rate, with only 5% of the population fully vaccinated. Vaccine shortages and confusion over the government’s vaccination plan both contributed to the low vaccination rate.

The new lockdown measures weighed heavily on AUD, seeing it drop to a one-week low against the Pound despite the difficult week for GBP. It’s likely that the new restrictions will dent the country’s economy, especially now that Australia will halve its international arrivals, impacting the tourism sector.

GBP/AUD Exchange Rate Forecast: GDP to Support the Pound while Lockdown Weighs on the ‘Aussie’

With the coronavirus crisis in Australia unlikely to improve overnight, GBP/AUD could gain some more ground next week. AUD investors will be looking at how the Australian government handles the surging cases, and whether the situation worsens or improves.

The UK and Australian Markit services PMIs are out on Monday. Both figures are expected to fall slightly, but the higher forecast figures for the UK may support GBP over AUD.

Also on Monday are Australia’s final retail sales figures. After the disappointing preliminary figures, any upward revision could bolster the ‘Aussie’.

However, the interest rate decision from the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) early Tuesday morning may see the Australian Dollar slip. The RBA took a dovish stance in its previous policy meeting, and with the Delta variant spreading across the country it’s likely to maintain the same stance.

The Pound Australian Dollar exchange rate may rise even higher at the end of the week, as the UK’s GDP three-month average is projected to rise from 1.5% to 3.9%, boosted by the further reopening of the UK economy.
